rom early adoption of the Internet by the Association of Nigerians Living Abroad and their Niajanet virtual community, the grassroots organizing efforts that led to the phenomenally successful Million Woman March, the migration of several historic black presses online, and an interventionist critique of race in contemporary video games. Ultimately, Digital Diaspora shows how African Americans and African diasporic peoples developed the necessary technomastery to ride in the front of the bus on the information superhighway.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican Americans and mass mediazUnited States. 0aAfrican diaspora. 0aComputersxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aDigital mediaxSocial aspectszUnited States. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aAmerican Studies : American Culture. 4aArea Studies : African Studies. 4aCommunication : Intercultural Communication. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978079147720540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791477205423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791477205/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles